      <hedline>
        <hl1>NBC in Sydney: The Judges Frown</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eldar Rapaport letter says NBC's television coverage of Olympic events in Sydney should be more complete, and some events should be broadcast live despite time difference (Sept 20 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''NBC's Ratings for Olympics Are Worst Ever'' (front page, Sept. 20):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''NBC's Ratings for Olympics Are Worst Ever'' (front page, Sept. 20):</p>
        <p>It is not surprising that NBC is getting low ratings for its Olympics coverage. Yes, Sydney is 15 hours ahead, but 7 p.m. prime time here is already 10 a.m. the next day in Sydney. At least some of the early competition could be live.</p>
        <p>Furthermore, we get to see only fragments of a competition. This is especially apparent in men's and women's gymnastics, where we get to see only selected routines, mainly American. The dozens of montages and endless high-drama sappy stories  should be dropped. Audiences would like to watch sports. After all, that is what the Olympics are.</p>
        <p>ELDAR RAPAPORT  New York, Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
